"height": 75}], "section_name": "U.S.", "word_count": "1360", "source": "The New York Times", "subsection_name": null, "lead_paragraph": "For the past few years, researchers have been holding forums to see how people would ration limited medical resources during disasters or pandemics.", "pub_date": "2016-08-22T04:00:00+0000", "news_desk": "National", "headline": {"print_headline": "Whose Lives Should Be Saved? To Help Shape Policy, Researchers Ask the Public", "main": "Whose Lives Should Be Saved? Researchers Ask the Public"}, "print_page": "9", "snippet": "For the past few years, researchers have been holding forums to see how people would ration limited medical resources during disasters or pandemics....", "_id": "57ba5d7b95d0e021d7981e26", "slideshow_credits": null, "abstract": "Researchers in Maryland, in effort to shape public health care policy, have been asking American citizens for their opinions on rationing and allocating medical resources in large-scale emergencies like disasters or epidemics;  effort is among the first times that a state has gathered informed public opinion on such questions before devising policy on them, and hope is that outcome can help shape national model. "}